******
[1] Liberia: possible sexual transmission
Date: Fri 1 May 2015
Source: CDC/MMWR Early Release / Vol. 64 [edited]


Possible Sexual Transmission of Ebola Virus -- Liberia, 2015
------------------------------------
What is already known on this topic?
Ebola virus persists in seminal fluid following recovery, but the duration of viral shedding and the likelihood of sexual transmission are not known. Earlier studies have demonstrated that the virus can be isolated from semen as long as 82 days after symptom onset, and that semen can be positive by reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction, indicating presence of viral RNA, up to 101 days after onset. Possible sexual transmission was reported in 1968 for Marburg virus, a related filovirus, but has not been clearly documented for Ebola.

What is added by this report?
Ebola virus can persist in the seminal fluid of convalescent men for longer than previously recognized and can potentially lead to sexual transmission of Ebola.

What are the implications for public health practice?
Until more information is known, contact with semen from a male survivor should be avoided. If male survivors have sex (oral, vaginal, or anal), a condom should be used correctly and consistently every time. Additional studies are planned to examine Ebola virus persistence in body fluids of male and female convalescent patients and the likelihood of sexual transmission... - much more

[Multiple authors - see source]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Scientists can't say definitively, but it appears that the Liberian woman contracted Ebola from unprotected sex with a male Ebola virus disease survivor. Previously, it was believed that the Ebola virus can survive in semen up to 82 days after a patient is considered cured, but there has never been a documented case of this happening, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention report. Tests of the man's semen, performed 199 days (6-1/2 months) after he 1st developed symptoms, found Ebola RNA. This suggests the genetic material can remain in semen much longer than previously known. However, another woman he had sex with around the same time tested negative. - Mod.LK]

[On 18 Sep 2014, a man was tested Ebola-blood-negative in West Africa. He was finally released from airport quarantine in New Delhi after testing Ebola-semen-negative in mid-March 2015, 6 months after he was declared Ebola-free in West Africa; see ProMED archive (61) below. - Mod.JW]

