[According to the Shanghai Science and Technology Commission, an Ebola diagnostics kit produced by Shanghai ZJ Bio-Tech Co has been added to the World Health Organization's approved purchase list.]

Funding
----------
Wed 29 Apr 2015 Ghana: Barry Callebaut commissions Ebola center for General Hospital
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504291549.html?viewall=1
[Barry Callebaut, a cocoa trader, in collaboration with the Swiss Embassy and the Ministry of Health, has handed over an Ebola Medical Stores (building) to the Tema General Hospital. The project, which is estimated at a cost of GH cedi 80 000 (USD 20 779), forms part of plans to set up a trust fund to support health and education in cocoa growing areas globally.]

Wed 29 Apr 2015 Liberia: GAC wants all public funds officials bonded
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504291722.html
[Liberia's Auditor General has recommended all people who are taking care of public or government money be bonded. This will not only ensure professionalism and a good level of accountability but enhance transparency and ensure proper record keeping at a level where funds are expended.]

Fri 1 May 2015 USA: "Health care equity key to Ebola fight:" doctors, nurses petition Obama
http://www.pnhp.org/news/2015/may/%E2%80%98health-care-equity-key-to-ebola-fight%E2%80%99-doctors-nurses-petition-obama
[A petition was sent to President Obama, from more than 1400 health professionals, who say the Ebola epidemic is linked to global inequality and that African nations will require sustained US aid to build up their health systems. The authors call for a commitment by the United States to provide USD 8.4 billion annually (the equivalent of a single day's health expenditures in the USA) to Ebola prevention and treatment efforts in West Africa, and to build up the health infrastructure in Africa. - Mod.LK]

[It is self-evident that the health infrastructure in Africa needs to be built up, but that will take decades. My personal view is that as no epidemic was set off in the USA by the various imported cases, it might make more sense for the money to be spent in providing proper isolation facilities and training in large state hospitals to handle suspect cases of dangerous infectious diseases. - Mod.JW]

Vaccine, test, research
-------------
Fri 1 May 2015 USA: Doctors, nurses petition Obama
http://www.pnhp.org/news/2015/may/%E2%80%98health-care-equity-key-to-ebola-fight%E2%80%99-doctors-nurses-petition-obama

[In the same petition sent to President Obama, the authors call for a commitment by the United States to establish a public pharmaceutical company to develop drugs and vaccines in the public interest, given that private drug companies "failed to pursue an urgently needed Ebola vaccine because it offered little prospect of financial gain." I don't think a public pharmaceutical company would be able to compete for expert scientific staff with the existing pharmaceutical giants, who should be given financial incentives to compete to produce the best product the fastest. - Mod.JW]

Fri 1 May 2015: WHO approves China's Ebola test
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-05/01/c_134200736.htm
[The World Health Organization has approved an Ebola test reagent developed by a Shanghai firm, Shanghai ZJ Bio-Tech Co., Ltd. The real-time diagnostic kit has been listed as eligible for procurement and recommended to be used to diagnose Ebola virus disease.]

Sat 2 May 2015 USA: Ebola virus stability on surfaces and in fluids in simulated outbreak environments
http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/7/15-0253_article
[Abstract. We evaluated the stability of Ebola virus on surfaces and in fluids under simulated environmental conditions for the climate of West Africa and for climate-controlled hospitals. This virus remains viable for a longer duration on surfaces in hospital conditions than in African conditions and in liquid than in dried blood.]

